5️⃣ Entities (Database Design)

We will keep 3 main entities.

User

Represents a person using the app.

Fields:

User
----
id
name
email
password
createdAt

Relationships:

User 1 ---- * Expense

One user can have many expenses.

Expense

Represents a spending entry.

Fields:

Expense
-------
id
title
amount
description
date
user_id
category_id

Relationships:

Expense * ---- 1 User
Expense * ---- 1 Category
Category

Represents expense category.

Fields:

Category
--------
id
name

Examples:

Food

Travel

Bills

Shopping

6️⃣ Basic Operations (Minimal CRUD)

To keep it simple but useful:

User APIs
POST /users
Create user

GET /users/{id}
Get user

Later this will become:

POST /auth/register
POST /auth/login
Expense APIs

Core functionality.

POST /expenses
Create expense

GET /expenses
Get all expenses

GET /expenses/{id}
Get expense by id

PUT /expenses/{id}
Update expense

DELETE /expenses/{id}
Delete expense

Optional but good:

GET /users/{userId}/expenses
Category APIs

Very simple.

POST /categories
GET /categories
7️⃣ Database Relationships (Important for JPA)
User
  |
  | 1
  |
  |------< Expense >------| 1
                         |
                      Category

Meaning:

User (1) -> (Many) Expense
Category (1) -> (Many) Expense

This allows you to practice:

@OneToMany

@ManyToOne

@JoinColumn

Which is exactly what you will learn in Spring Data JPA.

